Democrats vs Republicans

In this study, I focus on U.S. Presidential inauguration speeches of 8 presidents in the recent 50 years . Here I conduct a brief comparison of speeches by the parties to which the presidents stand for. I am interested in the similarities and the difference of the speeches in terms of length and content.

List of Presidents of United States from 1969 to 2018

Part 1. Length of the Inaugural Addresses

In the recent 40 years, the average number of words used by each president fluctuate between 1200 to 2500.It seems like presidents of the Democratic Party delivered slightly shorter speeches, but the difference is not significant.Presidents known to have good public - speaking techniques, such as Ronald Reagan and Barack Obama, gave longer speeches.

Part 2. Textual Analysis

In the text cleaning process, besides the usual procedure, I manually removed some uninformative words such as will, can, and let and replaced some synonyms. After that, I plot word clouds of the most frequently used 100 words for presidents of 2 Parties and look at their similarity.

a.Republican

b.Democratic

c. Top 20 Words shared by Presidents of Two Parties
[1] 5.1 4.1 2.1 2.1

The most frequent words shared are America, people, world, nation, government, etc. This is expected because inaugural addresses are used to present presidents visions and goals for the country, their promises to the people, and the missions for the government. Words like peace, freedom are long-term goals that could not be emphasized enough. Here I am interested in the word history and want to know its context.So I found 10 words that are most correlated to the word history,and it seems like when the presidents look back in history,they care about aid they received, wins, threatens to lives of the people, and rebuilding the country.

d. Comparison cloud of top 50 words that appear in speeches from one party but not the other

Code from https://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/production/course_935/ch2_pdf_slides.pdf

It seems like presidents from different parties differ in philosophies. Presidents from the Democratic Party talk more about equality & health care, children land issues. Whereas presidents from the Republican party talks more about freedom, housing policies, state, and union. The findings matche two parties long term ideology.

e. Closer look at some ambiguous words and its syntax

Here again, I found the 10 words that are most correlated with the word never which appear very often in speeches from the Republican Party but not from the Democratic Party. Never which is associated with negative sentiments is related to immigration. For presidents of the Democratic Party, the word future is associated with dignity and school which is consistant with their political stands.

Part 2. Topics Modeling of Inaugural Speeches

I did LDA on inaugural speeches for all U.S presidents and take a close look at the 8 presidents we are interested in. We study how often presidents address seven topics: Economy , Equality, Misc, Legislation, Government, Reform,Freedom. In the plot of the average frequency presidents adresse those 7 topics, it seems like there is only subtle difference between parties.Republicans address freedom and government slightly more often than Democrats which is consistent from our findings before.

Finally we look at a cluster plot of the topics in Inaugural Speeches. Topics change over years, and the presidents in the recent 50 years cover similar topics compared to presidents from the old times. Its noticable that President Donald Trump and George Bush covered topics relatively different from the other recent presidents. Its also interesting they are both presidents of the Republican party. All presidents from the Democratic Party(in my analysis) cover similar topics.

Conclusion

For the 8 recent presidents, their inaugural speeches cover very similar topics but still differ by party. And when we take a closer look at the words presidents used in speeches, it seems like the contents differ by parties and match the partys ideologies.
